## The Operational Challenge

Your admin tool has 47 features. Your team uses 8. The other 39 are noise. The tool was designed around features. Your team works in [workflows](/process).

A feature-centric tool asks "what can this tool do." A [workflow](/process)-centric tool asks "what does the team need to do." The difference is the design starting point.

Here is how to design around workflows.

Custom admin dashboards and internal tools are critical for operational velocity. When operations teams are forced to use raw database views or developer-facing interfaces, task completion times slow down and error rates rise. Designing clear, role-based workflows in your admin panel ensures team members can act quickly and securely without needing technical support.

## Core Pillars

* **Map the workflows**: What does the team do every day. Every week. Every month. The workflows are the structure.

## Real-World Impact & Metrics

I redesigned a client's admin tool in 2024. The old tool had 47 features. We mapped the workflows. We identified 8 workflows. We built 8 screens. The other 39 features were removed. The team's task completion time dropped 35 percent. The tool was simpler. The team was faster.

### Performance Comparison

| Metric | Before Redevise | After Redevise | Improvement |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Process Cycle Time | Baseline | -35% | -35% reduction |

> **Strategic Takeaway:** For each workflow, define the screens. What does the team need to see. What does the need to do. The screen serves the workflow. Remove the features that do not serve a workflow. If a feature is not used in any workflow, it is noise. Remove it. The teams that design around features are the ones with bloated tools. The teams that design around workflows are the ones with focused tools.

